replies.bodyText:
It took me a while to see how this could be an issue but I think you mean cases like:
{
	"user": [{
		"name": "eve",
		"scores": [1, 2, 3]
	}, {
		"name": "adam",
		"scores": [4, 5, 6]
	}]
}

I see the fields API currently returns "user.scores": [ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6] here at the moment, so I will add a test to make the unmapped behaviour doing the same. Or did you think about a different case?

Interesting variation that cannot happen with mapped fields, but is accepted e.g. with "dynamic": false, since we have no mapping and type checks then:
{
	"user": [{
		"name": "eve",
		"scores": [1, 2, 3]
	}, {
		"name": "adam",
		"scores": "foo"
	}]
}

I think this should return the flattened "user.scores": [ 1, 2, "foo"] then, but maybe you disagree on that?

Thanks, I understand now. I investigated this and unfortunately it is not as straight-forward as it seems, at least I didn't find an easy way after a bit of searching. I now remember the reason I added the return type was another case I have in the tests. Consider this:
Mapping:
{
	"_doc": {
		"properties": {
			"obj": {
				"type": "object",
				"enabled": "false"
			}
		}
	}
}

Doc:
{
	"obj": ["string_value", {
			"a": "b"
		},
		[1, 2, 3]
	]
}

I would expect the fields output for obj to be [ "string_value, [1, 2, 3]] (note the list inside the list. Do do this I need to be able to add to the list collected when on the "obj" level (see  https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/pull/65386/files#diff-3c196c8a285307ef760ada7bc5a1df27dce1f4e7160bf75d028833793d171a9aR185).
At the same time the case above (adding to the same key from two different nested objects should return a single concatenated list) should work. I wasn't able to reconcile both cases without the return type so far.
If you agree with the above expectations on list-inside-list maybe we can leave this investigation for a follow up as well since its an internal anyway?

Got it, that is indeed a tricky example. I would actually expect that lists of lists get flattened, as we do for mapped fields. For example, we accept and index documents like this (although maybe we shouldn't):
{ "field": [[1, 2, 3]] }

The fields option will descend into the arrays and return { "field": [1, 2, 3] }. So maybe we can just do the same in your example and return { "field": ["string_value", 1, 2, 3] }.

